Bronze 4\par
By Rhea Romero\par
\par
Lobb and Inzy pushed their way to the southern end of the underground chamber.  They didn't make eye contact with each other once.  \par
\par
The southern passage was a mess of people going both ways and sometimes sideways.  Inzy had to stoop a little.  She was starting to feel like she'd gotten herself into something very not fun.  Here she was, in an undersized tunnel filled with short beings, with some foul-tempered mindless Hithual, heading off for a mission she knew nothing about.\par
\par
Lobb was going about with his usual calm and minimal air.  It wouldn't be hard to keep track of the tall Usil and apparently she knew where they were going, so he followed her without much to worry about.  If they messed up it would be her fault.  Easy enough.  \par
\par
Still, it wasn't smart to be on bad terms with your traveling partner, which Lobb knew all too well.  So after a few minutes of walking in silence he pulled her towards a small alcove and looked straight at her.\par
\par
"Usil," he said.  "We have a mission.  We have to work together.  Which means we have to like each other.  So let's make peace and continue."\par
\par
Inzy raised a skinny eyebrow.  "Okay, Lobb.  I apologize too."  She looked amused.  Lobb decided it was going to be very hard to keep on good terms.\par
\par
"So.  Where are we going now."\par
\par
"To the main line, Corky said."  Inzy squinted down the passage.  "Guess that's like, a really important mole hole."\par
\par
Lobb ignored the editorializing.  "How much do you think we can trust him."\par
\par
She looked surprised.  "Corky?  How much can we afford not to?  I mean, it's either follow his directions or run around blindly, you know, we aren't really in a position to question anyone, Lobb.  Until you remember your mission, we'll have to assume a LOT."\par
\par
He thought about this for a minute.  "I wonder," he said oddly, "how important this is."\par
\par
Inzy straightened up as much as possible.  "We'll have to assume it's the most important thing in the world," she said.  "Now let's get going, shall we?"  She smiled down at him and slipped back into the stream.  Lobb shrugged and followed.\par
