\pard ============================================================================\par
The Kings of the Forest (pt. 1)\par
by Dravon Soulkill\par
\par
We had been flying over a previously unknown kingdom the day before, west of a small hithual colony.  In the evening, we observed a large city near a forest, probably the capital of this region.  Great beauty graced this city's all-wooden architecture, so I decided to have a closer look.  Allon, Stoker, Bizzy and I landed just before dawn this morning, a few miles north in the forest.  The rumblings of a storm echoed in the dark.  The  Dirge remained up in the sky, watching for San warbirds among the clouds; since Dacklar's battle last week,  there had been no further sign of them.  I put Seltin in charge, with Dacklar at his side for in-depth combat training.\par
\par
No sooner had we set foot in this misty forest than the sound of battle arose.  The clang of metal and the mighty roar of a monster echoed through the woods.  We hurried to investigate.  In a small clearing stood a Griffon , poised to release its fiery breath at a gallant knight clothed in green.  The raging storm of fire fell upon the man as he plunged his blade into the beast's crimson-stained hide.  The knight fell to his knees-alive, but just barely.\par
\par
Horrified by the spectacle , we reached for our weapons, hoping to aid the knight.  Suddenly, I felt the cold edge of a blade under my throat. Move not, strangers," spoke a cool voice, "for this is not your battle." I glanced over and saw the warning came from another knight.\par
\par
Six other knights appeared around us.  They all wore the same green garb and armor as the noble warrior in the clearing.  We were evidently not to be killed, so our attention went back to the fight.  The Griffon pawed at the sword stuck in its chest,  trying to rip it out.  It prepared to breathe again.  Raising both hands the knight chanted a vigorous psalm.  \par
\par
Lightning suddenly flashed and struck the sword's pommel, driving the searing electricity straight into the Griffon's heart.  The Griffon coiled and uncoiled in agony.  Finally, roaring its pain at the thunder, the beast fell heavily to the ground. \par
\par
This knight was not elf, nor had he uttered a paladins spell.  What magic was this that allowed a knight to strike this griffin so deadly a blow from the skies?\par
\par
Clearing his throat, the knight before me put his sword away and said," King Pelet does get rather punchy in his morning!! Indeed.\par
\par
The king finally stood up and returned, wounded and burned, to his knights.  He was either a powerful man or very lucky. "Who are you strangers?" he asked.\par
\par
Dravon of Spur, and my escort." I replied\par
\par
"Eh? Never heard of it," grumbled the king." I am tired. Follow me to my camp."\par
\par
I could not help admiring the workmanship of the kings armor.  Tiny leaves and branches were delicately carved into the plates.  Then I realized this was no metal armor; it looked more like wood, perhaps petrified or somehow turned into metal.  In fact, all these knights wore he same style of armor, and their weapons, too were made of that odd iron. Dark green cloaks concealed the men well, except for the cloaks' delicate golden trim or the occasional glint of armor.  Their helms all bore large animal heads, and in the eerie morning mist they looked like surreal creatures of the forest.  Without waiting, the knights and their king all rode away.\par
\par
A bard alone remained. "They always do that," he said, "but don't let them intimidate you, my lord.  They enjoy playing hard to get comes with the forest.  I guess we'll have to walk, then." he said.\par
\par
On our way to the camp, our new friend told us more about our bizarre encounter.  The king was on a quest.  Forester tradition demanded that he return to the hollowed forest to meet his end should he fail his duty.  He had until next summer's forester's gathering to complete his quest.  He had to do so alone, without help from anyone, to prove his valor. This was very serious business for the foresters.  In this case, he was to slay a mother griffon, Graunax.  The one he had destroyed this morning was her daughter.  The king was still seeking Graunax's secret lair.  It soon became clear we were well within the forester's hallowed forest.  This caused  great discomfort to stoker. My first officer detested treading uninvited upon others' sacred grounds; Stoker had a great respect for things of nature, especially forest spirits.  A billowing fog rose from the ground.  It was so thick it could only be someone's uncanny magic.  Suddenly, a net fell from above.  We were captured with ease; within minutes, we and our bard friend stood before the foresters.  The foresters were angered. Bound and gagged, we were brought to the heart of the hallowed grove.  As we quickly learned, no one but a forester was allowed to enter the sacred woods.  Until late that day, a crowd of foresters debated on which god to sacrifice us to.  At last the high priestess questioned our bard friend.  Our situation greatly improved after they learned that the king had invited us to his camp after defeating the griffon.  Since we had a legitimate reason for being in this forest, they chose to set us free up to a\par
point, that is.\par
\par
Bizzy and Allon, why did it have to be them? why were they kept as hostages.  Stoker and I were set free to leave. We had until next moon to accomplish our business; only then would the hostages be released.  I had no quarrel with the high priestess of this kingdom, nor did I desire one.  Since the foresters showed only limited respect for foreign nobility, negotiation was of little help, and violence was out of the question.  At the bards insistence, we left without further arguments.  He feared for our safety, for the foresters could be cruel when offended.  Clearly our presence was offensive.\par
