\pard ============================================================================\par
Travels of an Odarian Priest\par
Memoirs of Khatmandu Snaggletooth\par
\par
My story begins in a little fishing village on the coast of Leuia where I was born. My father, Temeso, was a fighter in his younger days before meeting my mother, Jiriva. She was a priestess of Rinanni, the healer for our village. My father's love for her was so great, he devoted himself to Rinanni and her peaceful ways. He swore to only take up his sword again in defense of peace. His khat'sara gift to her was the sword his father had given him when he left home to seek his fortune. It hung over the fireplace in our house, the pearl amulet my mother gave to him set into the pommel. \par
\par
My earliest memories are of running along the beaches with my pet wolf, Jayke. We used to race the boats as they sailed in from a day's fishing. My father's boat was always the first one to dock. His osprey would take to the air, flying to our home to let mother know he was coming home safely. I would leap onto the boat, asking my father to take me with him the next day. He would laugh, pick me up and tell me to ask my mother. He would toss Jayke a fish and tell me stories about the Leuian Heros while he cleaned his catch. I would help him carry the fish home, Jayke dashing around us trying to get another meal. \par
\par
Mother would be waiting at the door, her dove nestled on one shoulder. She would make a fuss over the fish, and over how strong I was to carry them by myself. Dinner would be just about ready when we got home. Mother would send us off to the bathing pool, she always insisted we be clean for meals. After eating, we would join the rest of the village around the fire in the center of town. The adults would hold council, settling disputes, celebrating new khat'saras and births, discussing the events of the day, and planning for the future. I would sit with the khits, learning from the clawmasters. They would teach us our heritage, telling stories about great leuians and their deeds. They would teach us the rites and rituals of our kyn. We learned the names of the gods and goddesses, the history of Leuia, and most importantly, they would teach us to know honor. Most of my friends dreamed of the day they could undergo the ritual of Kit'ra and join the councils by the fire, I dreamed of the day I could be a clawmaster. There is nothing more honorable than teaching the young, I thought. \par
\par
Times were peaceful, and I began to believe this was the way of the world. Then, during the summer of my 5th year, a band of Pirates began raiding the coast. These honorless Tarr'khats followed the nameless one. Living off the work of others, taking instead of earning. My father's eyes were drawn more and more to the sword over the mantle. I noticed the steel had taken on a keen edge and shown with a faint sheen of oil. Rumors reached us that the Pirates had been sunk in one of the storms that come up so suddenly during the summer. We would occasionally find timbers from ships washed ashore that summer, so we believed the rumors to be true.\par
\par
My mother woke me one night, tears brimming in her eyes as she bundled up some of my belongings and told me to come with her. When I came out of my room I saw that my father had taken down his sword, and was belting it to his waist. He wore a battered suit of leather armor. He spoke quietly to my mother, kissing her on the cheek before coming to kneel before me.\par
\par
 "My son, you and your mother are going with the other khits and some of the elders into the woods. I will come to get you when it is safe. Jadr spotted the Pirate's ship a few moments ago. We will not let them take our village so easily." There was a fire in his eyes as he spoke, I could feel his claws dig into my skin as he hugged me to him. I could also feel the tear as it dropped from his cheek onto my fur. \par
\par
"Be true, son, be true." My father whispered to me before rising and hugging my mother one last time. His osprey flew from his perch, and followed him into the night. My mother took my paw, wiped her eyes and slowly looked around the room, memorizing every detail. Then she called her dove and my wolf, and we headed for the trees.\par
\par
I do not remember much of that night, only that every shadow seemed to be a pirate coming for me and my mother. Nothing could ever make me forget the next day however. Our village was decimated. The only thing the Pirates had not destroyed was the docks. I ran through the ruins of the town, calling my father. My mother ran behind me, begging me to stop, she knew what I would find. He was in front of our house, or the skeleton of it at least. His osprey lay in a crumpled heap of feathers, a cruel barbed shaft piercing his proud body. My father slumped against a wall, the sword broken beside him. He was still alive, but barely. There were several dead pirates scattered around him. My mother screamed his name and knelt beside him, calling on Rinanni to save him. One of the elders came and put his arm around my shoulder. "Come, you should not see this" He started to take me away when my father shuddered, the light in him dead. My mother roared, Jayke howled, and I knew no more.\par
\par
When I awoke, I was cradled in my mother's arms. She was keening softly, rocking me back and forth. I touched her cheek, tracing the path her tears had taken. She looked diminished somehow, as if part of her died with my father. When she realized I was awake, she took me to see my father one last time. Someone had cleaned him, and dressed him in his best leathers. His osprey was also beside him, still faithful in death. He had been placed on a bier, as had the rest of the slain. There was no moon that night, I remember thinking even the heavens were paying respect to the dead of our village. The village mourned that night, telling stories honoring the dead's lives. As the sun rose the next day, we lit the biers and released the spirits of our kyn.\par
\par
My mother and I left the village the next day. We traveled deeper into the forest, my mother becoming weaker with grief each day. Each night she would hold me in her arms and cry herself to sleep. Every morning she would watch the sunrise, her eyes focused on something only she could see. She wore the amulet of Rinanni once again, her paw straying to touch it as we walked. We had been traveling for 9 days when we came upon a monestary in the woods. This was the place my mother had learned to be a priestess. We were met by 6 leuians in robes. One dressed in red, another in green, one in blue, one in white, one in black, and one in yellow. They were the priests and priestesses of the religions. The woman in the white robe smiled and hugged my mother, calling her by name. The priest in the red knew my mother too, he smiled and bowed to her. \par
\par
My mother made arrangements for me to be instructed in the ways of the gods and we were shown to a room. That night my mother cried softly, telling me to be true. When I awoke the next morning she had joined my father.\par
\par
The first few months after my mother's funeral passed by in a blur. I had been included with a group of khits around my own age and was sent to classes with them. My mind constantly wandered, I could never remember the day's lessons when questioned about them. The only lessons I took to heart were the fighting ones. I eagerly awaited the clawing lessons each day. When the clawmaster would let us practice what we had learned on the targets, I would attack mine in a frenzy. I used to imagine that I was slashing the Pirates, exacting revenge for taking everything I held dear. I wanted no other purpose in life other than to see them dead at my feet. No book could help me gain my revenge I thought. \par
\par
One day Gist, the Taathian priest, sought me out in my room. He wanted to talk to me about his God and how he could help me in my quest for revenge. It would soon be time for me to devote myself to one religion if my schooling was to continue with the monks. Gist took me to the Taathian shrine and I watched the monks there pratice fighting with various weapons. They seemed so powerful, so swift. I was sure there were no fighters equal to them in the land. I was entranced..the fights were nothing but a blur of steel and wood. I asked Gist to teach me more.\par
\par
I would spend the time I was not at my lessons with Gist, learning about his God. My teachers frowned on this, as I was considered too young for some of what I was taught. I thought I had found the path for my life, to serve Taath and in serving him, to gain my revenge on the Pirates. One night, after a particularly grueling day of claw training, I returned to my room to find Tadeyo, the Odarian priest who knew my mother, sitting on my bed scratching Jayke behind his ears. Jayke gave me a guilty look and slunk out the door. Tadeyo stood, his eyes meeting with mine. He seemed to be judging me, weighing what he saw in my eyes. After a moment or two, he shook his head slightly and sighed. "Your mother would not be pleased..your father even less so. Search your heart, Khatmandu..know your heart and be true." Before I could say anything, he was past me and out the door. I was shaken to hear the last words of my parents, and that someone who knew them would think they would be ashamed of me. \par
\par
I law awake that night, fighting the drowsiness as I tried to understand why Tadeyo thought I was a disappointment to my parents. It was not long before sleep won the battle and my dreams claimed me. There are some who say the world of dreams can sometimes pierce the veil that seperates our plane of exsistance from the planes of the gods. I cannot say for certain, all I can do is relay the dream I had that night. If it was a dream, which I sometimes wonder.\par
\par
I was lying in bed, looking out my window when two birds landed on the window ledge. My father's osprey and my mother's dove. The osprey cocked his head to one side and regarded me with an unblinking eye, I could read the displeasure there. The dove cooed once and flew to my pillow, landing beside my head. I felt the whisper touch of her feathers against the fur of my cheek. The dove's eyes looked into mine and I could hear my mother's voice in my heart.\par
\par
"So young..and so full of hate. Have you forgotten what we taught you, my son? You are not meant to hate like this." A single tear formed in the dove's eye and dropped onto the pillow.\par
\par
"The Pirates killed you and father! Am I supposed to love them for that? Am I supposed to leave you unavenged? They will pay, mother..I promise you that. I will have my vengance, by Taath!" I sat up in bed, almost spitting the words out in my anger. I could feel the rage building inside me, my paws clenched into fists and I flet my claws dig into my palms. I was shaking, the anger too much for me to control. In my mind's eye I saw my father lying against our house, the dead pirates around him.  \par
 \par
The osprey screamed then, his wings flapping in agitation. My father's voice rang in my head, the anguish in it stinging me to my core. "Little Khat..look closely at the pirates around me..look at the blades some of them carry. Not all of the Pirates followed the serpent god..some followed Taath. Tadeyo was right..I am disappointed in you. I taught you to not hate, that all life has value." The osprey turned his back to me, and the presence of my father left me. The dove seemed to be sobbing quietly on my pillow.\par
\par
I turned to my mother's dove, the shame of my father's rejection cooling the anger inside me. "What would you have me do, mother? I cannot bear to think they will not be punished. The hatred I carry is too great to let go." \par
\par
The dove turned her eyes to me and I could feel my mother hug me to her one last time. "You never cried for us, my little Khat..speak to Tadeyo and Niniba..they will help you find your way. Be True, son..Be True.." The osprey had already gone, his departure unnoticed. The dove flew up, circled my room once and was gone. \par
I threw myself back into my bed and began to cry, the grief for my parents finally finding release. \par
\par
I awoke the next morning to find Tadeyo leaning against the doorframe. He had a slightly bemused look on his face, almost as if he knew of my dream. "Good morning, I thought you might like to take a walk with me to the rock garden. I like to meditate on my troubles there. You might find it eases your mind as well." He reached down and ruffled Jayke's fur. "You are welcome to come along to, Jayke. I'm sure you'd enjoy basking in the sun." \par
\par
I dressed quickly, eager to learn what I could from Tadeyo of my parents. I felt a pang of guilt when I thought I would miss my morning lesson with Gist, in my heart I still longed for revenge. We left the khit's dormatory and headed for the opposite side of the compound to an area I had not visited before. Tadeyo's rock garden was incredible. There were numerous rocks of different sizes, shapes and colors. they were all 'planted' in sand that had been raked to form intracate patterns. To me, it appeard to be so many islands strewn about the sea, the lines in the sand the swirls of the current and the eddies of the tides. I asked Tadeyo if that was the intention, and he told me that each person sees the rocks differently. Some only see rocks in the sand. I felt sorry for those people. \par
\par
Tadeyo picked up a rake and crossed to one of the larger rocks near the center, carefully smoothing the footprints out as he went. I, being younger and smaller, decided to use the rocks as stepping stones and joined him on his rock. Jayke rolled happily in the grass, his tounge hanging out of his mouth. \par
\par
"You see, young one, even in the midst of something that at first glance appears chaotic such as this garden, when you study it fully and see it with new eyes, you learn that there is an underlieing order to all things. A harmony if you will. It took me many years, but I finally got your father to open his eyes to that." He had folded his legs underneath him and placed his hands on his knees. "No..do not question me here. Look inside yourself and ask yourself those questions."\par
\par
With that, he began to chant, the muscles in his face relaxing, his breathing getting shallow. I stared at the garden for some time, not thinking anything at all. After a while, I started to think about all the things my parents had taught me about being Leuian and what that meant. Soon, I was reflecting on what I had become over the past few months, remembering the black obsidian blades the Taathians used..seeing those same blades clutched in the hands of several of the Pirates. I saw what I was becoming, the lessons I had ignored flashing back to me. Taath, while a necessary god, was the antithesis of everything my parents had brought me up to be. He thrived on hate, and nurtured that hate in his followers. If I went down that path, all my father and mother had meant to me and to each other would be nothing. But I also knew I could never take the path of my parents, I would protect those that could not protect themselves.\par
\par
I felt Tadeyo's gaze, almost understood the question there. "Tadeyo, tell me what you know about my parents, and about Odarous." The time slipped away that day as Tadeyo talked to me about my parents. Other priests of various religions came to the garden, but most only lingered for a few moments of meditation before leaving us. Jayke used the time to chase butterflies, his jaws snapping in vain at them. For the first time since we had left our home, he was content. I kept expecting Tadeyo to preach to me about Odarous being the one, true god, as Gist had done with Taath. I was to be disappointed, he did not even speak to me about Odarous until many days later.\par
\par
As we were leaving the garden, Gist appeared. His black robes were billowing around him, his eyes flashing with anger. He did not seem to notice Tadeyo there, the storm of his anger was directed at me. Lifting me off the ground with one fist full of my robe, he spat curses at me for missing the lesson today. I clawed at him, hoping to get him to drop me. A snarl crossed his face, his anger rising. "You strike at me?!? Insolent khit, you know not what you have done!" He shook me once, then started to slap me with his free paw, berating me all the while. I was helpless, the shaking and the slapping addling my wits. I could hear Tadeyo screaming at Gist to stop, that I was too young to dedicate to a god yet. Gist threw me to the ground, my head striking a rock. Blinking the stars away, I struggled to get up. My feet seemed to ignore my commands, however. Jayke stood over me, his hackles raised and an ominous growl rumbling in his throat. \par
\par
Tadeyo and Gist were close to blows, each starting to circle the other. Tadeyo attempted to position himself between the Taathian and I, Gist extending his claws to rend flesh. Tadeyo stiffened, his tail twitching in agitation. "So be it, Gist.. Terms of the duel?" Gist smiled as Tadeyo spoke, his arms beginning to move in an intricate gesture. A pair of runic tattoos glowed on his body, then danced around his head. Tadeyo gasped in outrage, cursing Gist as a white aura surrounded my protector, his body fading from view as the aura diminished. Gist advanced on me, a smile of triumph on his face.\par
\par
"You were so close..so close to being one of us. But there are still ways you can serve." He cast another spell, this time a black vulture circliing his head as he stood over me. Jayke growled and crouched lower, preparing to spring at Gist. Gist chuckled softly, his claws darting out and finding Jayke's body, flinging him to one side. Red bolts of pain flashed across my ribs, the link I shared with my wolf causing me to feel his pain. Gist grabbed me by the scuff of my neck, dragging me in the direction of the Taathian shrine. I was helpless to resist, the blow to my head addling my wits still. We had almost reached the shrine when a grey blur launched itself at Gist's back. Jayke had come to my rescue. His jaws were locked on the hamstring of the priest, forcing a strangled cry from my captor.\par
\par
Jayke shook his head, severing the tendons in the back of Gist's leg. He crumpled to the ground, writhing in pain. Spewing curses, he beat at Jayke's head. I heard Jayke yelp and saw him stagger back, shaking his head to clear it. Gist cried out Taath's name and a black cloud formed over his head. In the wink of an eye, he was gone. Jayke whined, his worry for me coming across the link. "I'll be fine, Jayke..just a bit stunned is all..thank you my friend." The wolf came over to me and lay beside me, sharing his warmth with me until I could stand. I tended to the scratches on Jayke's side as best I could, then we headed off to our room.\par
\par
I asked if Tadeyo or Gist had been seen, but no one could tell me where they were. I spent the rest of the day in my lessons, wondering what the other service I could preform for Gist was. I wanted nothing to do with the Taathians anymore after my experiences of the day. Gist would not involve me in anything involving Taath again, I vowed. \par
\par
When the moon rose, the two priests still had not returned, and many began to wonder aloud what had happened to them. I had my suspisions about Gist, as the Taathians all cast baleful looks my way. I thought I was too troubled to sleep that night, but I drifted off to sleep. Something woke me, a muffled sound penetrating into my dreams and rousing me. I could not see anyone, but I could feel presences in my room. I was about to cry out when a paw clamped over my mouth, strong arms pressing me into my bed. Jayke whined, his fear flooding back to me. Something had grabbed him, entrapping his body in a net of blackness. I fought to free myself, to come to the aide of my wolf. A voice came from the darkness, whispering into my ear. "This is all your fault..you should not have turned from us..."\par
\par
I was wrapped in the bedsheets and slung over someone's shoulder. After a short journey, I was dumped to the ground. It was hard to concentrate, Jayke's emotions overpowering my thoughts. I could feel his heart racing, mine beating faster as well. When I could see again, I was laying on a black marble floor at the foot of a dark altar. Gist was standing behind it, chanting words that seemed to squirm in the air before me. Something was draped over the altar. Gist picked up a serrated knife, brandishing it above his head as his chant intensified. I quested for Jayke, feeling his terror..but he was not terrified for himself, he feared for me. I tried to calm him..to let him know that everything was alright when the figure on the altar moved.  It was Jayke.\par
\par
He turned his golden eyes on me and sent a wave of love over our link at me. He howled, and I heard "Be true" in my head. I started to roar then, watching helplessly as the blade plunged down, ending the life of my last and best friend. I screamed at Gist, struggling to break free of the grip that held me and to kill Gist.\par
\par
"That takes care of your cursed mutt..once the altar is ready again you will join him." Gist hobbled around the altar to loom over me. The leg Jayke had savaged was bound and splinted, but it was obvious he would never walk right again. I hoped Jayke knew that he had crippled his killer. He motioned for a priest to take the body of Jayke from the altar, another stepping forward to cleanse the blood away.\par
\par
Gist was in the midst of lighting another stick of foul-smelling incense when the doors burst on their hinges, showering everyone with splinters. Several of the priests yelped in pain as the splinters bit into flesh. Through the door came Tadeyo and the priestess of Rinanni who knew my mother, Niniba. There were several other leuians with them, all with bastard swords forged from tiger-eyes or pearls.\par
\par
Tadeyo was unarmed, his white fur shining. "I have come to claim the rite of Klaaw'vor, Gist. You dishonor our race with the actions you have taken this day." Tadeyo fixed each of the dark-robed priests with his gaze, the leuians at his back ready for battle. Niniba stood to one side, leaning on an ash staff carved with the symbol of Rinanni. "I have no wish to involve anyone other than your high priest, kyn..any who wish to leave may go now. On my honor, no harm will come to those that do. If you remain, my friends and I must believe you support this vile, flea-infested furred go-blin, for he cannot be called a leuian after today." In response, the Taathians all drew the obsidian blades they wore. \par
\par
Tadeyo nodded once. "We dance then, kyn. I bow to your courage and your honor." He bowed to the Taathians once, and they returned the bow. Chaos erupted then, blades and runes flashing as the two sides crashed together. Shouted insults and challenges rang in the chamber. Cries of pain and anger filled the air as well. Gist cast weave after weave into the crowd, sometimes calling on Taath to strike one of Tadeyo's group. Niniba stood at the rear, the Taathians ignoring her as she called to Rinanni to restore those who fell on her side. Tadeyo moved like liquid fire, his paws and feet swatting away blades and dealing out blows in a blur of motion.\par
\par
The battle was a dance, I saw. Especially the way Tadeyo fought. He spun and leaped, striking his opponents in the joints of their armour or at exposed areas. Gist was cursing his priests, urging them to kill the Odarian fury fighting through the press of bodies toward him.  Niniba was pulling the fallen to the side now, her favors exhausted. She ignored none, Taathians were still kyn. Gist muttered something about protections and cursed Rinanni.\par
\par
Tadeyo pulled the helm from the head of the last Taathian between him and Gist and tossed it to the floor. Slapping the man's scimitar to the floor, he grasped the leuian's head and slammed his forehead to him. A sickening crunch echoed in the chamber, the priest crumpling bonelessly to the floor. Gist called on Taath again, beseeching his God to smite Tadeyo. A flash of darkness surrounded the Odarian, when it cleared, he was on one knee, but still alive.\par
\par
"You will not be rid of me that easy, Gist. You are not the only one who has the protection of his god." Tadeyo stood, whispering the name of Odarous. A glowing golden eagle formed over his head, the wounds he had taken closing shut. "This ends NOW!" The scattered fighting ceased at Tadeyo's commanding shout. Several Leuians on both sides crumpled to the ground in exhaustion.\par
\par
"Gist, will you redeem yourself by accepting my challenge of Klaaw'vor? Or have you sunk so low that you have no honor left?" Tadeyo flung his words like a gauntlet, Gist wincing visably at them.\par
\par
I felt a cool paw touch my shoulder, and saw Niniba kneeling over me. "It will be alright, Khatmandu..fear not."\par
\par
Gist bowed his head, considering his plight. The clerics still alive and conscious moved among the fallen, dressing wounds and offering what comfort they could...but no one took their eyes off the pair on the dias. "Very well, Tadeyo, I accept your challenge. My sword against your claws, to the death. Agreed?"\par
\par
Tadeyo nodded once, a grim look on his face. He looked over to me and bowed his head slightly. "This ends with your death or mine, Gist. The boy goes free and none seek revenge for what has happened tonight. Understood?" I knew he asked if I understood, not Gist. Gist agreed and I nodded to Tadeyo.\par
\par
Gist's blade was unlike the other Taathian's, his was jagged, the darkness of the blade seeming to linger in the air when he swung it. I had never seen the dark priest fight before, but his skill with his weapon was evident. He swung the heavy blade easily, it was an extension of his body as he moved. The wound in his calf hampered him some what, but Tadeyo seemed reluctant to take advantage of that. They came together, exchanging blows faster than the eye could follow. when they separated, each had slashes and cuts on his body. Tadeyo seemed to be tiring quicker than Gist, the exertion of his claws draining him quicker than the black blade drained Gist.\par
\par
They crashed together again, niether one giving ground. Whereas the larger battle was filled with shouts and cries, the only sound of this battle was the scrape of foot on stone, the whistle of the blade through the air, the quick gasp as claw or sword found flesh. Each was bleeding from half a dozen wounds or more, Gist with one great slash across his chest, one of Tadeyo's arms flayed to the bone. Gist pressed his attack at Tadeyo's injured side, the Odarian struggling to defend himself. A misstep gave Gist an opening and his blade bit deep into Tadeyo's side. A grin of victory spread over Gist's face, the sight of his foe staggering back giving him renewed energy it seemed. The blows from his sword rained down on Tadeyo with a new fury. Tadeyo was able to keep Gist at bay, but each blow warded sapped him of his rapidly diminishing energy. Gist roared and raised his blade over his head, preparing to cleave his exhausted opponent with one mighty blow. As the blade descended, Tadeyo dropped to the ground and lashed out at Gist's exposed abdomen with his claws. The blade smashed into Tadeyo's shoulder, lodging itself in the bone there. Tadeyo's claws ripped through the black leather, disemboweling the Taathian. Gist stumbled to one side, his nerveless fingers releasing his sword and clutching his stomach. He groaned once, and collapsed to the floor, dead.\par
\par
Tadeyo wobbled to his feet, his blood drenching his white fur. Niniba hurried to him and offered her shoulder in support. "It is finished..honor is satisfied, kyn." With that, he lapsed into unconsciousness.\par
