\pard ============================================================================\par
Welmar\par
By Guztymne Horawytz\par
\par
The sky was purple the night that Welmar died.  Rather, he was killed by assassins.  I was at the window sill when it happened, and who could forget the gory scene?  The assassins did not notice me because I did not make a sound as I leapt onto the ground below.  From the second storey, it was quite a feat.  Fortunately, I was not hurt, and rushed off to find some source of help.\par
\par
In the merchant's circle, people were walking to and fro, in haste and with greed in their eyes.  I avoided their stramping on me, and quickly fled to a lonely corner.  I glanced back at the busy street and sighed.  Did no one see my worry?  Could no one read my mind from the silence, from the fear in my eyes?  Was my trauma not apparent in my skin?  Softly, but discontented, I wandered to the Apothecary's guild, where guilded scholars were learned in the different arts of apothecary.\par
\par
Contrary to Alchemists, members of the Apothecary guild were learned in the arts of the written word.  Welmar was once a member of the guild, but changed his profession into something simpler.  He opened a blacksmith shop and led a quiet peaceful life, antithesis to his loud public figure in the past.  Always, I was there with him.  Perhaps, it was because he saved my life that gave me such loyalty to him.\par
\par
In the dark of a cold winter night, I was left crying in the middle of the street, Welmar would tell me.  He had found me that night while he was inscribing scrolls for the governor then.  My cry pierced the still of the night, and Welmar could do nothing until he came out of his splendid house and saw me naked, left by my mother to be torn by wild beasts in the middle of the night.  As he approached me, he saw a Yelican in the shadows, about to leap at me, about to paw me under its tremendous weight.  Welmar chanted some quick magickal words and runes appeared, causing a foul fog to encompass the Yelican.  Shrieking, the Yelican fled back into the darkness of the forest.  Welmar picked me up in his strong arms and from then, I was his constant companion.  Women of his life came and left, but I was always there since he took me under his wing.  When I was younger, he would sing lullabys for me.  Stroking my fur, he would close his eyes and sing tunes of ancient lores and bardic melodies.  It was like paradise.\par
\par
When he moved out of his mansion to be a blacksmith, as he had always wanted to be, he brought me with him to a little hut by the river's edge.  He decorated the house and painted it all like he wanted to- in shades of purple and violet.  That was his color, and the governor of Spur had only allowed black and white houses- this was what he wanted to do, and at last, he was free.  There, we had our quiet subsistence by ourselves.  His constant monologue and my consistent attention were all we needed.  Caviar were never part of our meals, but we never starved- he always found fresh meat for me, and took care of me just as well as when he was richer.\par
\par
A stomp on the ground.  I looked up, and saw a young man looking straight at me.  I purred, and he picked me up.  I tried to tell him about Welmar, but he was ignorant of my language.  He cuddled me and walked out of the guild with me in his arms.  An image clouded my vision, and I was not sure what was going on.  It was Welmar, lying in the pool of his blood, a narrow stream flowing from his body to his shelf of books.  It was Welmar, with his mouth torn by the vicious assassins, his breath cuddled with blood as he coughed his essence of life.  It was Welmar, the only one who cared.\par
\par
The smell of incense permeated the air.  I blinked and the apparation of Welmar was gone from in front of my eyes.  I looked up, and realized that the young man was gone.  In his place was a black-cloaked figure, holding me in his gloved hands.  He laid me on a cold obsidian table.  This looked familar.  The black candles and incense- the drops of blood- skulls laying carelessly around the floor.  Welmar had sung about the altar sacrifice- Oh God!\par
\par
I sprang to my feet, and hissed at the figure.  I extended my claws and stood on my toes, prepared to fight for my life.  The figure just stood there, motionless.  A soft chanting was the last things that I heard before a bright light burst into me and I feel, asleep.\par
\par
The next few minutes, or hours were unclear to me.  It was like a dream, but I was immobilized.  Somehow, in my sleep, I could see the world outside of my head.  The figure was there, and he held above my body a blunt knife.  Before he could mash my ribs with the knife, something vague happened.  It was not clear, but was like a purple fog- a soft violet miasma covered the entire altar.  The figure was circled by this thick transculent magenta-purple fog.\par
\par
I opened my eyes.  I remember the purple fog.  Welmar.\par
