\pard ============================================================================\par
Killing List -- Arrival\par
By:  Soulstar Sunflare\par
\par
It's been twenty years, the shadowy figure thought to himself as he glared down at the sleepless city from atop a far hill, twenty years and so much has changed.\par
\par
Once, long ago, he could have made a grand entrance into the city.  Very few would have opposed him.  And of all those that would try, none would have lived to tell about it.  But now, only twenty years since his departure, his very race could mean death for him.\par
\par
The man turned quickly at the rustling of grass behind him, his sword half drawn.  There behind him was a rat wandered through the brush, chittering quietly.  The man snorted and drew the Max Rehas Unbreakable Black-Diamond Bastard-Sword completely out of its scabbard.  In one swipe, he lobbed the rats head off and sheathed the sword.\par
\par
Turning back to study the city, he noticed a torch coming toward him.  The man growled quietly, drew a throwing dagger, and slipped into the shadows.  He watched the light as it continued to move closer and the figure carrying it became visible.  A pathetic human street urchin rounded a bush and walked by where the man was hidden.  He was hardly worth a dagger and the man let the urchin pass by.  Then he got up and slunk along the road toward the city gates.\par
\par
He stopped a little over fifteen feet from the gates and took cover behind a rather large conifer tree.  He reached into the back pack he had been carrying and pulled out various odd contents that only a thief would be likely to recognize easily.\par
\par
A San Elf fighter should work well , he thought as he gazed into a hand held mirror and applied a darkening agent to his face and hands.\par
\par
When he was satisfied that his skin was dark enough to pass as a San Elf, he pulled out another content from his pack and began dying his silver-white hair to a raven black.  The dye he used dried quickly and left him more then enough time to change his clothing from an authentic Black-Silk Three-Piece Rehas Suit to a garb more appropriate to that of a fighter.  He pondered for a moment whether or not to wear his Gold-Embroidered Black-Silk Rehas Cloak, but quickly decided against it.  Instead he dawned the heaviest thing in his pack, a Max Rehas Black-Diamond Chainmail.\par
\par
Equipped as he was, and his disguise firmly set, the man turned to change the final item of his disguise.  His ID badge.  He glanced down at the thin metallic pin that was still fastened to the vest of his suit and smiled.  His real name was engraved in that pin, even though it could not be read in the virtually nonexistent light from the sliver of moon that hung just above the horizon.  As much as he loved that name, he dared not wear it for any of his missions.  Instead he pulled another pin out from the pocket of the leggings he now wore.  He tipped it to face the pale moonlight so he could be sure of what was inscribed into it.  On it was the name he used for ever one of his missions.  The name that he had never failed a job with.  Chade Daggerfall.\par
\par
The man quickly fastened the pin on the left side of his tunic, just above his heart, and took on the identity it gave him.  Chade repacked his backpack and shouldered it.  Then he stood up and strolled over to the gate.  He glanced up at the two guards as he passed under the open arch, but they paid him no mind.\par
\par
Probably too busy playing with their dice, he thought with a snicker as he entered the outskirts of the city.\par
\par
The silence that persisted outside the city walls did not within them.  Just a few meters in from the gate, Chade was assaulted from all sides by various sounds.  There was a constant hum from the north, of which he knew was issued from the town square.  To his left he heard the death scream of a rogue.  Vaguely interested, he glanced toward the now fading scream to see a Thugian tear off the arm of its victim and gnaw on it.\par
\par
Chade snorted in disgust at that.  Though starving Thugians made great torture tools, the very sight of one eating its own kill was not a welcome one to him.  He continued on up the road without looking back as he heard another death scream from where the Thugian hunted.\par
\par
He passed through another, smaller, gate and came upon a rather large inn.  He didn't need to look at the sign outside the inn, he knew it was the Guilded Lion Inn.  He had fond memories of this place.  It was where he and his long dead wife had stayed while on their honeymoon.\par
\par
Chade sighed at the memory of his wife and tried not to remember how she had died.  Unfortunately, it was not a scene he could ever forget, for his dreams always brought it back to him.  She had been killed by a group of Frontacian runemages in this very Inn.  Her head removed before his eyes and placed on a pike in TSC for all the city to see.  How he had escaped the same fate he never knew.  He had blacked out when his wife was decapitated.\par
\par
Chade's mind had been so preoccupied with that memory that he did not notice the Secian that flew in and hugged him until it was already flying into the waterfall room.  Wondering if the waterfall was still there, he looked toward the Secian and saw, to his surprise, many more fluttering about.  Though he never got along well with Secians, he was amazed to see so many gathered together in one place.\par
\par
Perhaps a meeting, he thought as he shook the notion of asking them from his mind.\par
\par
Chade searched for the inn keeper and found him behind the front desk.  He rented a room for the next few days and left.  He traveled north until he reached another gate.  He stood there for a moment, listening to the ruckus from farther north.  He glanced up at the sky and knew the sun would be rising soon.  He'd have to be back at the Inn before then, but first, he wanted to go to check out Town Square.\par
\par
Chade passed through the gate and within moments was standing at the edge of Town Square.  Almost everyone in TS was gathered in the very center and chatting about virtually anything one could imagine.  Most however seemed to be listening to, and singing along with, a bardic Hithual.\par
\par
Chade slipped into the crowd and proceeded toward its center.  There he not only got a better view of the Hithual, but also saw the group of bards that surrounded him.  There were a couple of Drag-als playing flutes, an Anthain with a harp, a Secian who sang along with the Hithual (but was drowned out by him as well), and a Human who beat rhythmically on a set bongo drums.  The tune they played was a very merry one.\par
\par
Merriment not being one of his favorite things, Chade soon became bored with the crowd. He was about to return to the Inn when a large group of Secians swept passed him and landed by the one who was already singing.  Their voices quickly joined in the song.  Chade stopped one Secian as she flew by his head and gave her a ruby.  The little one stopped for a moment to pocket the gem and Chade took that chance to ask her why everyone was so happy.\par
\par
She giggled at him and said, "Because it is the Vernal Equinox.  Why else."\par
\par
First day of spring, he thought as the Secian hugged him and flew away to join her friends, figures.\par
\par
Chade turned from the crowd and walked back to the Guilded Lion Inn.  He went up to his room and dropped his pack at the end of the bed, then closed the curtains on all the windows.  He sighed in relief and took his disguise off.  When he finally finished with that, he opened his pack and rummaged through it.  He pulled out a list of names and scanned over it.\par
\par
Chade put the list away a few minutes later and laid down on the bed.  Even as sleep drew near he thought of what he was going to do.  Tomorrow he would have to find the first person on that list.  Tomorrow that one would die as few others have in a very long time.  Permanently.\par
\par
(To be continued\'85)\par
