A Flickering of the Light\par
by Kyrinne Woodmist\par
\par
\par
The night wind howled like a banshee as it raced and whirled through the deserted streets of Spur. Floating upon the bitter wind were wails and blood-curdling screams, the dreaded dirge of yet another battle in town square.  Beneath the arch, a heartless Drag-al named Tony pushed and shoved a secian as if he were nothing more than a worthless toy.  He grabbed him roughly by the collar of his wool shirt and dragged him through the dirt in the direction of Executioner\rquote s square.  He dealt Kento a cruel blow with his golden sword and sneered as he pushed him into the filthy pit where the bodies of Spur\rquote s worst criminals are slowly reduced to slime and sludge.  Terrible cries filled the air as Kento screamed for help, his senses reeling from the stench of putrefying flesh and the pain of the ragged slash across his forehead.  He could hear the Drag-al laughing as he left, obviously lost in the sick afterglow of his perverse sport.  Kento struggled to stand amid the slippery gore and braved the darkness of the pit with his tiny wings.  Up into the skies he flew.  Up where the air was clean and fresh.  Up where he could breathe once more.  \par
\par
Kento healed his wounds and returned to town square only to find the very same callous Drag-al eager to repeat his wretched game.  Once again Kento was pushed to the ground while the Drag-al and Incense, a Leuian, laughed wickedly, their empty black eyes fitting companions to their barren souls.  Over and over, they continued their loathsome game until finally Kento and Kyrinne could bear no more.  Kyrinne tried to comfort Kento, took a deep breath, and pointed to the giant sign.\par
\par
\ldblquote Please stop pushing,\rdblquote  she pleaded, her voice taut with apprehension and fear.  The two bullies only laughed at her; their faces flush with the obscene pleasure of harassing the defenseless. \par
\par
\ldblquote I am tired of your mouth,\rdblquote  the Leuian hissed at Kyrinne.  He had been angry with her ever since they had quarreled over the senseless death of Raptoriann, a secian he had killed in town square for no apparent reason.  After his murder more deaths had followed.  Benni, Cappy, Laeytrob, and many, many others fell beneath the smite and storm spells he cast with such reckless abandon.\par
\par
He spat and howled at her, his maniacal voice ringing through town square like the ranting and raving of a madman.  The Drag-al snickered quietly in the background as he nodded to his companion and rubbed his hands together as if trying to warm them or rub something off.  The Leuian poked Kyrinne in the ribs and pushed her down, grinning at her with a mouth that resembled a steel trap designed to snap the limbs off rabbits.  She shuddered and cautiously stepped away from him, her breathing rapid and shallow from the fear that gripped her.\par
\par
\ldblquote I am tired of your pushing,\rdblquote  she cried as she stood up; her heart racing so fast she could barely breathe.  She understood her words could very well mean her death, but what could she do?  She was so incredibly tired of running and hiding in the shadows while Spur\rquote s bullies roamed the streets free to kill with no fear of repercussion.  Like so many others, she was weary of watching secians being harassed simply because they refuse to respond with anything other than words.  Voices on the wind sometimes carried memories and speculation about secians defending themselves-defending themselves like in the days long before they bonded with dragons.  She tried hard to push away her anger just as she knew Kento was struggling to restrain himself from saying what he was thinking too.  They took silent comfort in each other\rquote s presence and waited.\par
\par
Incense laughed, grinned wickedly and pushed Kyrinne again.  The Drag-al laughed, snickered at Kento, and abruptly pushed him to the ground too.\par
\par
\ldblquote What will you do?  Sic your dragons on me?\rdblquote  the Leuian asked Kyrinne, his eyes betraying the sickness that fouled his mind.  He snickered and batted his eyes at her as she shivered in revulsion.  She watched helplessly as the Drag-al grabbed Kento by the hair and dragged him out of view.  She sighed heavily, tears welling in her eyes.  She wished there was a spell to cure a blackened heart.  Demeralda found something special in Incense to love, but sadly Kyrinne could find nothing there to love at all-only a black hole where his heart should have been.  All she could see was a vicious murderer who had no respect for life, not even the lives of those who loved him.\par
\par
\ldblquote I have no animosity towards you.  I just want you to stop pushing.\rdblquote  she explained, hoping to prevent the inevitable violence that seems to be his only course of action.\par
\par
\ldblquote You lie,\rdblquote  he spat.\par
\par
\ldblquote I do not lie,\rdblquote  she said, shocked that he would even suggest such a thing.\par
\par
\ldblquote You\rquote re a wicked feral, a bad secian,\rdblquote  he accused falsely.  He pointed straight at her and howled, his breath foul from the stale blood of his many victims.  Kento, who had just returned from the infamous pit, was tempted to laugh at the ridiculousness of his statement, but thought better of it when he saw the evil glint in Incense's eye.\par
\par
\ldblquote No\rdblquote  she said firmly, her temper beginning to rise.  \ldblquote You lie,\rdblquote  she added before she could stop herself.  The very second the words passed over her lips she knew she had erred.  But even as he cast his first spell she knew she would not have done differently.  There comes a time in everyone\rquote s life when they must take a stand and she understood that this was such a time.  She could no longer bear to witness the bullying and harassment-quite simply, she had lost the ability to look the other way.  She had seen too much.\par
\par
Some laughed, some smirked, some shrieked and some looked away as she stumbled and fell unconscious, blood flowing from the ragged wound across her throat.  Like a ruby colored halo, blood formed a crimson pool around her head where she lay among the trash, vomit, and broken wine bottles.  Kento shrieked in horror as her lips quickly turned from the color of cherries to the pallor of a white rose and her cheeks lost their lovely blush.  He sighed in despair as the Leuian quickly dragged her out of town square toward the south.  He called to her telepathically, but heard nothing but silence.  \par
\par
Panicked voices called back and forth across Spur as secians tried to discover Kyrinne\rquote s whereabouts and arrange for her rescue.  After much searching, Rixinon finally found her lifeless body in the bottom of that loathsome pit, a place where none of her brethren could hear the cries of her ghostly voice.  A place where she could not be resurrected.  While Rixie worked with others like Tisha and Minerva to remove her cold and frail body from the pit, Kyrinne\rquote s mind drifted into the past.  She remembered how Benni, Cappy, Laeytrob and many others were murdered just a few weeks ago by a storm spell from the very same hand that just took her life.  \ldblquote Everything happens so fast,\rdblquote  her ghost said quietly to no one in particular as her eyes closed and memories filled her head.\par
\par
***************\par
\par
As the Leuian withdrew, his cold laughter echoed eerily through the still streets of Spur.  Leaves whirled madly in the wind and fell to the ground like puppets who lost their strings.  Dozens lay dead and several lay dying, their fading heartbeats whispering in the stillness.  Suddenly, the wind returned and whipped harshly through town square, sucking the warmth from their cooling flesh like the deadly caress of a Muatana-al.  Ghosts moaned and wailed from their abyss of defeat, crying for resurrection or cursing their poverty before departing and facing the house of the dead.  Among the dead lay a secian whose ghost lingered in a strangely silent vigil.  Other ghosts floated above her and spoke in hushed tones, recounting the terrible attack, while this one secian said nothing. \par
\par
There at her feet he lay, his broken body as cold as ice.  She could only stand there staring blankly like a statue, stunned by all the storm spells, all the deaths, all the violence.  In her confusion she didn\rquote t even think to pray to Sa to resurrect Cappy.  She just stood there staring at his lifeless corpse, tears slowly streaming down her face.  His solemn silence belied the torment in his heart-the bitter fruit borne of sheer desperation.  When the Leuian had cast storm spells at dozens in the now-bloodied square, she had seen a certain spark in Cappy\rquote s eyes slowly fade and disappear.  Like the sun fades in the gloom of dusk, his hope withered in the shadow of such appalling violence.\par
\par
Laeytrob\rquote s crumbled form vanished as he departed.  Cappy sighed heavily and frowned.\par
\par
\ldblquote I know it\rquote s wrong.  But I will do it again if I have to,\rdblquote   he said, his hands clenched into fists.  \ldblquote I am tired of doing nothing, tired of being powerless, and tired of looking the other way.\rdblquote   He ran his hands through his hair and muttered something beneath his breath.  Kyrinne said nothing.  Instead, she pulled him close to her, held him in a warm and tender embrace, and listened quietly as he spoke of his frustration.\par
\par
\ldblquote I know I disappoint you and I am sorry for that,\rdblquote  he sighed as he took her hand in his.\par
\par
\ldblquote No, Cappy.  You mustn\rquote t say such a thing,\rdblquote  she sighed softly.  She kissed him gently and leaned her head on his shoulder.  \ldblquote I know what\rquote s in your heart,\rdblquote  she said tenderly.  \ldblquote You\rquote re a fine secian and you could never disappoint me.\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote I am tired of just standing there and doing nothing.\rdblquote   His face was strained and pale and his brow tense.  He sighed heavily and stared off into the distance, his frustration and regret nipping away at him like the sharp teeth of a killer rat.\par
\par
\ldblquote I know.  But you can heal.\rdblquote  she said quietly reminded him.\par
\par
\ldblquote It\rquote s not enough.  He killed Benni for healing,\rdblquote  he replied angrily.  \ldblquote I never thought I would pray to harm anyone, but I had to try to stop him from casting more storm spells.\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote I understand how you feel, my love,\rdblquote  she replied.  \ldblquote Spur seems ruled by a few bullies and we seem to be their favorite victims.  Sometimes I wonder if anyone cares....\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote I know I will do the same again.\rdblquote  he sighed.  \ldblquote I think it\rquote s best I left Spur for a while.  I don\rquote t want to bring shame upon us and I know I will.\rdblquote\par
\par
Her heart sank to hear he no longer trusted himself for she knew him to be gentle, kind, and loving.  Like a dreadful prophecy of chaos and shame, his actions haunted him.  What would he do the next time?  Would he pray harm again?  She turned her head away so he would not see how much his words troubled her.  If only tears could revive the river of peace that she knew flowed inside everyone\rquote s heart.  If only Benni hadn\rquote t been killed for healing someone in town square.  If only the governor cared about a safe town square.  If only Spur was a kinder place.\par
\par
***************\par
\par
In her lovely sapphire dress, Rosi danced with Rixinon in town square, laughing and giggling when Kyrinne arrived.  Rosi gave her a big hug and pointed to a giant sign that now stood near the arch.  Kyrinne almost fainted when she read it: City Code 134.532:  There will be no fighting, sparring or brandishing of arms within Town Square.  Failure to abide by this code may be punishable by fine, imprisonment, or a more severe penalty in the case of multiple offenses.  Rosi laughed and tickled Kyrinne, who could only stand there gaping like an idiot in stunned disbelief.\par
\par
\ldblquote Wow.\rdblquote  Kyrinne finally managed to say. \ldblquote I don\rquote t believe it.\rdblquote\par
\par
Rosi clapped and the three of them danced happily around time square until they ran out of breath from too much excitement.  Soon, Pepperi, Pear, and other secians arrived and joined the celebration.  Laughter and music rang through the town square as fine instruments, rosewood mandolins and guitars, pipes, and drums were pulled out of sacs and songs were played-happy songs to match their high spirits.  Passerbys must have thought a festival was taking place, so gay and joyous were they as they flittered and fluttered around town square without fear for the first time in many months.  Or was it years?\par
\par
A muttering Go-blin-al entered the peaceful square, read the sign, and smirked.  \ldblquote Stupid sign.  Who put that there?\rdblquote  he asked.  He grumbled a bit and kicked the sign a few times.\par
\par
\ldblquote Um, you might not want to do that,\rdblquote  Rosi suggested wisely, unsuccessfully hiding a smirk behind a small, pale hand.\par
\par
Kyrinne stopped playing her pipes and raised an eyebrow at Rosi.\par
\par
\ldblquote Why not?\rdblquote  the Go-blin-al asked, muttering something beneath his breath about stupid signs.\par
\par
\ldblquote Well.\rdblquote  she replied, but before she could explain further a Justice appeared and announced that the Go-blin-al was under arrest for damaging public property.  The Go-blin-al scowled, kicked the sign again, and was heard yelling \ldblquote It\rquote s not fair\rdblquote  as he was hauled off to Spur\rquote s jail to serve his well-deserved sentence.\par
After the snickering and laughing died down, the music played on.  Well, at least for a while.\par
\par
A San Elf and a Leuian entered town square, obviously intent on killing each other.  Their clothes were saturated with blood as if caught in a ruddy rainstorm, their eyes squinting and tense, and their hands tightly gripped on their weapons and shields.  The San Elf slashed fiercely at the Leuian with his blazing sword, but his attacks seemed to have little effect.  Barely alive, his muscles taut with forced energy, the San Elf struck one final blow before he was surprised by the appearance of the Justice.  Life\rquote s blood leaked from the ragged slice across his face as he heard that he and his \ldblquote friend\rdblquote  were under arrest for violating City Code 134.532.\par
\ldblquote What\rquote s this nonsense?\rdblquote  the San Elf demanded of the Justice and scowled.  He tended to the gash across his face as he impatiently waited for an answer. \par
\par
\ldblquote We were only....um sparring.\rdblquote  the Leuian grunted as he leered at the San Elf with eyes than promised their \ldblquote spar\rdblquote  was not over.\par
\par
\ldblquote Read the sign,\rdblquote  replied the Justice.  \ldblquote Ignorance of the law is no excuse.\rdblquote\par
\par
In a split second these two friends found themselves in what was to be a very popular destination that day.  The jail.  They moaned and whined to each other, cursing the unfair justice system, stupid laws, or their foolishness-perhaps a fair measure against their honesty, insight, or temperament.  Sadly they were neither the first nor the last to learn Spur\rquote s justice system has little mercy.  If anything, Spur\rquote s justice can be called swift.\par
\par
For the first time in many months, secians could sit in town square and play a few songs without being afraid of who might suddenly appear.  They forgot about bullies and violence, but instead reveled in the knowledge that the governor cared.  Soon their fingers were bruised from the strings of their instruments and their voices hoarse from laughter and song.  Later, when each one of them took to their beds, their faces wore a smile even when sleep took their thoughts to another realm.\par
\par
***************\par
\par
\ldblquote Kyrinne?\rdblquote  Minerva asked as she shook her gently.  \ldblquote Kyrinne?\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote Hmm....\rdblquote  Rixinon mumbled as he poked her and called her name once more.  \ldblquote Kyrinne?\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote What...? Kyrinne asked, disoriented.  \ldblquote What happened?\rdblquote  \par
\par
\ldblquote Rixinon rezzed you.\rdblquote   Minerva said, gently stroking Kyrinne\rquote s hair.  \ldblquote I know it was a shock being in that pit, but you\rquote re okay now.\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote I was dreaming,\rdblquote  Kyrinne said as she blinked and shook her head.\par
After many warm embraces to thank and comfort, Rixinon and a grateful Kyrinne returned to town square after a brief stop at the bank.  The square was filled with Dragons, San Elves, and Leuians-the strong, the curious, the good, the evil.  Some were there by chance and some were there by curiosity while others were there because they had an interest in the day\rquote s events.\par
\par
The winds whispered with words in Secian, words that spoke of frustration and feelings of helplessness.  Like a whirlpool, words swirled and whirled around the square catching many in their path.  In the aftermath of violence, promises and threats were made.  Dragons fumed and possibilities were considered.  \par
\par
Was this the fifth secian murder in two weeks, or the sixth or seventh?  Should these cruel episodes of a serial murderer be ignored ?  Was there any justice in Spur?  Was the giant sign just a piece of wood?  Was it just an empty gesture?  Such questions weighed heavily upon many who were tired of the constant and unabated violence in town square.  Dragons grumbled and considered their options, some secians ventured nowhere alone, and Spur waited to find out who controlled Spur.  Was it the governor or a few bullies?\par
\par
As would be expected, some saw this new development as an opportunity to test the governor\rquote s patience-that giant sign saw more kicks than a hand cleric would see in a lifetime.  More secians were attacked and many of Spur\rquote s residents chafed at the unrelenting plethora of uncontrolled violence, the lack of common courtesy and respect, and the sheer idiocy of those who think they can take the lives of innocents without any repercussion.  Unbeknownst to most citizens, the governor was meeting with his Justices and a few of the most noble in Spur, his Knights.  He had read scrolls about citizens longing for a safe place and heard the grumbling of his Knights who wanted to avoid racial wars-something everyone feared.  Would a champion bring justice or would the governor?\par
\par
***************\par
\par
Several Taathians lounged about town square, laughing and snickering about their most recent victim when a Justice suddenly appeared.  The Taathians appeared amused until the Justice stated his business.\par
\ldblquote Kryger, you are under arrest for murder.\rdblquote  the Justice announced.  \ldblquote Justice will be served.\rdblquote\par
\par
Kyrinne stared in disbelief, wondering where the Justice had been the night she had been killed.  \ldblquote There is no justice in Spur,\rdblquote  she said sadly as tears welled in her eyes.  \ldblquote We die and nobody cares.\rdblquote   She quickly left the square before she cried or said something she would later regret.\par
\par
\ldblquote Why is there no justice for us Pepperi?\rdblquote  she called to her mother telepathically.\par
\par
\ldblquote I don\rquote t know, dear.\rdblquote  Pepperi replied sadly. \ldblquote But why do they think killing someone is justice?  It serves no purpose to keep anyone safe for long...Why can they nae just be locked up for a while?\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote Why do they do nothing for us Pepperi?  We die and nobody seems to care.\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote When those who break the law are punished swiftly, they will stop breaking the law,\rdblquote  Obscure, the Justice responded telepathically to secians.\par
\par
\ldblquote Not ones like that...he\rquote s never learned before.\rdblquote  sighed Pepperi sadly as she furrowed her brow.  Too many memories of too many deaths filled her head.\par
\par
\ldblquote If he loses some of his constitution a few times he\rquote ll learn quickly,\rdblquote  Obscure replied sagely.\par
\par
\ldblquote Many never learn.  Spur is ruled by bullies and I am weary.\rdblquote  Kyrinne sighed.  She remembered Cappy lying there dead at her feet.  She remembered how he felt.  She remembered it all too well.\par
\par
\ldblquote How come we get killed?\rdblquote  asked Daphne.  \ldblquote We small but not powerless.\rdblquote\par
\ldblquote I could never hurt anyone,\rdblquote  Kyrinne sighed.  \ldblquote Never.\rdblquote\par
\par
\ldblquote If anyone touches me, I will do anything I can to survive.\rdblquote  Daphne replied quite honestly.  She clearly was not willing to become the next victim.\par
\par
\ldblquote Nor could I, dear daughter.  But in a strange way tis comforting to know that somethin\rquote  is being done.  My heart aches to see it, but perhaps it\rquote s time we see that sometimes it\rquote s necessary.\rdblquote  Pepperi added.  She knew that too much death, too much violence, and too much misery makes for a very poor life in Spur.  Each visit brought her less pleasure than the one before- a disappointment felt by many who believe in the path of peace.  She prayed for justice to be fair and merciful and hoped that Obscure was right.\par
\par
Secians spoke of peace, violence, and death for a while and pondered on the meaning of life in Spur while Kbar became the next to feel the heavy hand of justice.  Sadly many others followed.  Some were fined, some were executed, and some were imprisoned as Obscure proved that the giant sign was more than just a stick in the ground.  Some served their sentence willingly while others vainly tried to escape from the penalties of death and loss.  The following day the post office was flooded with scrolls about the state of justice in Spur.  Where were the fair trials or restitution for the victims?  Since that fateful day swift justice has made its appearance on a more regular basis, often much to the surprise of those who have long ignored the law.  Naturally some citizens were quite pleased with the actions of the governor, his knights, and the justice system while others ironically labeled justice unfair-particularly those who were known to be Spur\rquote s worst lawbreakers.  Justice restored some hope, yet many still worried that the fragile peace in town square was only temporary-just a momentary respite from the wretched bloody massacres that had permanently stained the soil a deep russet brown.\par
\par
Regardless of their fears and concerns for survival, Secians kept to their vows of peace and tried to comfort those who mumbled about taking up arms if the need ever arose.  Like a fragile flower that flourishes with care and perishes from the lack of it, the flame that lights the dark streets of Spur needs love to burn brightly.  So they turned to each other for comfort and courage and dreamed and prayed for a better life.  A life where they could heal someone or speak without being struck down.  A life where they could enjoy just a little of the peace that meant so much to them.  With justice firmly in place, including plans for the Knights to someday dispense justice, hope was slowly restored in the hearts of those who walk the path of peace.  After the long and terrible storm ended, the fierce winds that carve the rugged landscape of Spur often carried the voices of many very brave and loving Secians.  If you listen very carefully you may still hear them whispering the wise words of Jubbal: \ldblquote Love Everyone.  Respect Everyone.  Forgive Everyone.\rdblquote\par
